p.
  I first came across DataCentred at Lancaster University's SCC (School of Computing and Communications) Careers Fair last year. After applying for an intern position for the Summer, I was accepted onto the programme and spent the three months working on internal projects for the company.

p.
  In the days prior to starting here I was unsure what to expect. Twelve weeksÂ later, it's clear I joined at a very exciting time for DataCentred, its customers, and the cloud computing industry as a whole. As I come to the end of my summer internship here, I'd like to reflect on my - indeed, our - achievements of the past few months.

p.
  At our site in MediaCityUK, Manchester, we're developing a next-generation data centre and open source cloud computing services. Like many "Dev Ops" teams, we also practice agile development, which aims to create a productive, flexible and goal-orientated way of working. This has been key to the remarkable progress so far, and to us taking customers on board in such a short amount of time. Indeed, these customers (including my university) are now putting our hard work to good use. As more customers approach us with their often bespoke requirements, we have considered the best way to support them; in particular a way for them to identify issues, communicate with us effectively and also still let us practice agile development in this support itself.

p.
  Many off-the-shelf products meet these goals in many respects, but there were compelling reasons to build such a support product in house. Firstly, the product can meet any number of our own (and our customers'!) specific requirements. Secondly, the product can be a 'native' part of our existing customer-facing application. Finally, and perhaps most importantly, the product can integrate with JIRA, "the tracker for teams planning and building great products" - our go-to platform for agility. To say the least, it's really useful to track customers' issues and standard work requests - and our own platform development work - in the same environment. Thus, it was decided that we'd build our own bespoke, JIRA-powered system for managing Support Tickets inside our existing customer-facing management console.

p.
  This customer-facing management console is written in Ruby on Rails. This was my first time writing Ruby (and developing with Ruby on Rails, for that matter) after years of writing PHP for the traditional LAMP stack. Moreover, it has been my first experience of the agile way of thinking and writing automatically tested, production quality code in every case. We soon made another major technical decision in that the front-end for the application would be powered by AngularJS, which would allow us to create an expressive, dynamic interface without users having to explicitly refresh the page.

p.
  The result is an attractive web application for raising support tickets and following their progress until the issue is resolved. This was my main focus whilst working at DataCentred (although I also patched PHPIPAM to support decent LDAP authentication!). The tickets are represented in (and fetched from) our JIRA instance via the JIRA API, while the front-end automatically updates via AngularJS as issues are resolved and our team communicates with the customer to whom they belong.

